<section class="card" aria-label="Frequently asked questions about tomatoes in Zone 3">
  <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

  <h3>Can tomatoes grow in Zone 3?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes, early-maturing varieties can grow successfully
    when transplant timing allows sufficient seasonal heat accumulation
    before the first fall frost at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong>.
  </p>

  <h3>Should I choose cherry tomatoes?</h3>
  <p>
    Many cherry varieties require fewer total heat units
    than large slicing types.
    They often provide stronger margin in Zone 3.
  </p>

  <h3>What if I transplant in June?</h3>
  <p>
    Late transplanting compresses the ripening window.
    In Zone 3, even small delays can shift projected maturity
    beyond the frost boundary.
  </p>

  <h3>Can row covers improve reliability?</h3>
  <p>
    Row covers may reduce light frost exposure,
    but they do not materially increase total seasonal heat accumulation.
  </p>

  <h3>How much buffer should I leave?</h3>
  <p>
    A planning buffer of approximately 7–14 days
    between projected ripening and your average first fall frost
    improves reliability in short-season climates.
  </p>
</section>

